@NODE CONFIGMINI "ScreenShell.guide/Minimum configuration"
                           @{u}@{b}Minimum configuration@{uu}@{ub}

    ScreenShell  use new functions and tags from Kickstart 2.04+.  You must
so  have an Amiga with this minimum Kickstart version number.  The presence
of AGA chipset will increase the speed but is not necessary.

    ScreenShell  was  developped  and  compiled with SAS_C 6.51 on an Amiga
4000/40 with 18MO of RAM and an A4091 SCSI2 controler.

    Tested configurations :

    Machine        FAST CHIP   Controler      HD      Kickstart   Workbench
    A4000/040.25     16    2   A4091 SCSI2    1,2go      40.62       40.42
    A4000/030.25      8    2   A4000 IDE      250mo      39.106      39.29
    A3000/030.25      6    2   A3000 SCSI1    105mo      39.106      39.29
    A1200/020.14      0    2   A1200 IDE      80mo       39.106      39.29
    A2000/010.7       2    1   HCD+  SCSI1    52mo       37.175      38.30

    Tests with Enforcer 37.49 didn't show anything abnormal.

@ENDNODE

@NODE INSTALLATION "ScreenShell/Installation"
                               @{u}@{b}Installation@{uu}@{ub}

    Installing  SShell is realy simple.  Copy the file "SShell" in a drawer
in  you  "path" (eg:  "C:").  Copy "ScreenShell" and its icon in the drawer
"Workbench:System/".   Copy  the  doc  files  from the drawer "English/" to
where you usualy put documentations (eg:  a "Docs/" directory).

    ATTENTION :

    Do  not  attach  an  icon  to  the  SShell program directly.  You would
certainly  cause  a deadend crash at launch.  SShell mut be used from Shell
only.  If you want to use it from "Workbench" (see chapiter
@{" Use from Workbench " LINK UTILWORKBENCH}) you must launch the ScreenShell icon instead.

@ENDNODE

@NODE UTILWORKBENCH "ScreenShell/Use from Workbench"
                             @{u}@{b}Use from Workbench@{uu}@{ub}

    If  you  want  to use the full screen Shell from the Workbench you have
two solutions :

    - Doubleclic on the "ScreenShell" icon ;

    - Selecte the menu "Workbench/Execute command...", and enter "SShell".
      You could add some options here. see chapiter @{" SShell Options " LINK OPTIONS} ;

    @{u}Quit :@{uu}

    When  you  have  finished  working  with a SShell screen, type the keys
"Ctrl \\" or enter the "EndShell" command.

    @{u}Changing ScreenShell options :@{uu}

    ScreenShell  is a command sccript which execute SShell.  If you like to
midify  the  launch  parameters  of  SShell,  you  just have to modify this
script. Use your favorite text editor to do that.

    For example :

    Select the "Workbench/Execute command..." menu and enter :

    Ed SYS:System/ScreenShell

    Find  the  line saying "SShell".  Add the varying options right to this
command. (See chapiter @{" SShell options " LINK OPTIONS}).

    @{"Modify the options now !" SYSTEM "Ed SYS:System/ScreenShell"}
@ENDNODE

@NODE UTILSHELL "ScreenShell/Use from a Shell"
                             @{u}@{b}Use from a shell@{uu}@{ub}

    If  you  want  to  fully  use  ScreenShell, you must execute the SShell
command  from  a  Shell  or  a  Cli.   You  will  gain direct access to all
available options.  (See chapiter @{" SShell Options " LINK OPTIONS}).

    When your Shell Prompt appear, type :

    SShell [options]

    Add options to the right if you want.


    As  SShell  doesn't  return  until  it  is closed, you can use the "RUN
>NIL:" command tu execute it as a background task.

    RUN >NIL: SShell [options]

    @{u}Quit :@{uu}

    When  you  have  finished  working  with a SShell screen, type the keys
"Ctrl \\" or enter the "EndShell" command.
@ENDNODE

@NODE OPTIONS "ScreenShell/Options"
                                 @{u}@{b}SShell options@{uu}@{ub}



    @{u}The following options are accepted by SShell :@{uu}


    @{" FROM          " LINK FROM}    Execute a script at launch
    @{" SM=Smart/S    " LINK SM}    Disable cut and paste
    @{" NR=Noreq/S    " LINK NR}    Disable system requests
    @{" RT=RMBTrap/S  " LINK RT}    Disable menu display
    @{" ID=ModeID/K   " LINK ID}    Select a screen mode
    @{" C=Colors/K/N  " LINK COLORS}    Select the number of colors
    @{" W=Width/K/N   " LINK WH}    Choose the screen width
    @{" H=Height/K/N  " LINK WH}    Choose the screen height
    @{" OS=Overscan/K " LINK OS}    Select overscan type
@ENDNODE

@NODE FROM "ScreenShell/Options/FROM"
FROM                If  you  want  to  execute  a command script other than
                    "S:Shell-Startup"  at  start,  you  can  specify a name
                    here.

                    Example :   SShell FROM T:Hello-Startup   @{" Try " SYSTEM "Path / ADD
SShell FROM Hello-Startup"}

                    By default :    FROM S:Shell-Startup
@ENDNODE

@NODE SM "ScreenShell/Options/SM=Smart"
SM=Smarg/S          If  you  think  that  the scrolling speed on the SShell
                    screen  is still too slow, add this option that disable
                    "Cut/Paste" and speed up display.

                    Example :   SShell SM                       @{" Try " SYSTEM "Path / ADD
SShell SM"}

                    By default :    inactive
@ENDNODE
@NODE NR "ScreenShell/Options/NR=Noreq"
NR=Noreq/S          If you dislike to be disturbed by a system request each
                    time there is an error, add this option.  In case of an
                    error,  you  will  no  longer be disturbed.  The system
                    will act as if you had hit the "Cancel" button.

                    Example :   SShell NR                       @{" Try " SYSTEM "Path / ADD
SShell NR"}

                    By default :    inactive
@ENDNODE
@NODE RT "ScreenShell/Options/RT=RMBTrap"
RT=RMBTrap/S        By  default  menu  shows at a right mouse button press.
                    This   let   other   programs  attach  their  menus  to
                    ScreenShell.   The  excellent  "KingCon" from (1) David
                    Larsson is well used here.
                    But  if  you  prefer  to work without any menu, you can
                    activate   this   option   which   will  disallow  menu
                    displaying.

                    Example :   SShell RT                       @{" Try " SYSTEM "Path / ADD
SShell RT"}

(1) KingCon is a replacement for "CON:".  It brings new functionnalities as
jumpy scroll, menus, command history and a scrolling bar (not yet supported
by  SShell).  I have highly appreciated this utility which work well and is
complementary with SShell.

    To contact the author of KingCon:   David Larsson
                                        Engineering Physics
                                        Chalmers University of Technology
                                        Sweden
                                        (internet: f92dala\@dd.chalmers.se)
@ENDNODE

@NODE ID "ScreenShell/Options/ID=ModeID"
ID=ModeID/K         SShell  usualy  open  a  screen  the  same mode as your
                    Workbench  screen.   You will find sometimes usefull to
                    force  SShell to use another mode, not interlaced, more
                    high  resolution  or  whatever  you  want.   After  the
                    keyword  ID, add the hexadecimal value corresponding to
                    the mode you want.
                    (See @{" Screen modes identification " LINK "ModeIDe.doc/main"}).

                    Example :   SShell ID=19000                 @{" Try " SYSTEM "Path / ADD
SShell ID=19000"}
                                (NTSC:640x200 screen)

                    By default :    Identical to Workbench
@ENDNODE

@NODE COLORS "ScreenShell/Options/C=Colors"
C=Colors/K/N        SShell can work with either 2, 4 o 8 colors.  Usualy an
                    4  colored  screen is the best compromise between speed
                    and ANSI characters legibility.

                    You have juste to specify the amount of colors you want
                    here : 2, 4 or 8.

                    SShell  will open a screen with the requested number of
                    colors and will adapt its palette this way :

                    2 colors :      background      black
                                    text            white

                    4 colors :      background      black
                                    text            gray
                                    bright text     white
                                    colored text    blue

                    8 colors :      background      black
                                    text            red
                                    bright text     green
                                    colored text    match ANSI

                    Example :   SShell C=8                      @{" Try " SYSTEM "Path / ADD
SShell C=8"}
                                (ANSI eight colors)

                    By default :    C=4
@ENDNODE

@NODE WH "ScreenShell/Options/W=Width,H=Height"

W=Width/K/N         You  can  consider  usefull  to  force a given width or
H=Height/K/N        height  to the SShell's screen.  You may want a smaller
                    or  a  bigger  than  normally  displayed  screen.  (see
                    options (@{" OS=Overscan " LINK OS}).

                    Example :   SShell W=640                    @{" Try " SYSTEM "Path / ADD
SShell W=640"}
                                (forced width of 640)

                                SShell W=1024 H=1024            @{" Try " SYSTEM "Path / ADD
SShell W=1024 H=1024"}
                                (square of 1024 by 1024)

                                SShell H=960                    @{" Try " SYSTEM "Path / ADD
SShell H=960"}
                                (forced height of 960)

                                SShell ID=11000 W=640           @{" Try " SYSTEM "Path / ADD
SShell ID=11000 W=640"}
                                (640 pixels wide screen
                                 diplayed on a NTSC:320x200)

                    By default :    (Depend on the workbench's selected
                                    screen mode and overscan type)
@ENDNODE

@NODE OS "ScreenShell/Options/OS=Overscan"

OS=Overscan/K       Select  the  overscan  type.   It  could  be usefull to
                    select  a  largest  overscan  even  more  if  you own a
                    multisynchrone  type monitor and you are working in one
                    of  the  31Khz modes.  (eg:  DblNtsc, Productivity...).
                    In  these  modes,  standard scaled overscan leave large
                    unused black area all around the screen.

                    SShell accept 4 values next to the OS keyword :

                    TEXT :      No overscan at all
                    STANDARD :  Normal overscan (just a bit larger)
                    MAX :       Maximum overscan (a bit more larger)
                    VIDEO :     Chipset's maximum (the largest)

                    Example :       SShell ID=99004 OS=VIDEO    @{" Try " SYSTEM "Path / ADD
SShell ID=99004 OS=VIDEO"}
                                    (DBLNTSC:640x400 very large)

                    By default :    OS=TEXT
@ENDNODE

@NODE TESTANSI "ScreenShell/ANSI characters test"
                          @{u}@{b}ANSI characters test@{uu}@{ub}

    To  verify display quality and speed when you have opened SShell with a
specific  option, you can do a display of the test file "@{" ANSITest.doc " LINK "ANSITest.doc/main"}" by
typing one of the following commands :

    Type ANSITest.doc
                                                @{" 2 Colors " SYSTEM "Path / ADD
SShell C=2"}
    ou                                 Try :    @{" 4 Colors " SYSTEM "Path / ADD
SShell C=4"}
                                                @{" 8 Colors " SYSTEM "Path / ADD
SShell C=8"}
    More ANSITest.doc
@ENDNODE
